# SkillsHub — Cursor Rules
# Read this entire file before writing any code.

## What This App Is

SkillsHub is a markdown sharing platform for companies and teams.
Users share AI agent markdowns — skills, rules, prompts, SOPs — within their
company, with team-scoped feeds, cross-team approval flows, direct shares,
and per-MD ratings that aggregate into a per-author "Coworker Grade".

Built with Next.js (frontend) + Supabase (backend, auth, database).
Hackathon scope: functional first; deployment is optional (local `next dev`
is sufficient for the demo).

---

## Stack

- **Frontend**: Next.js 14+ App Router, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS
- **UI components**: shadcn/ui (initialized with `npx shadcn-ui@latest init`)
- **Icons**: lucide-react
- **Forms / validation**: zod (used inside server actions)
- **Backend**: Supabase (Postgres + RLS + Auth)
- **Markdown**: react-markdown + remark-gfm + DOMPurify (XSS sanitization)
- **Markdown styling**: `@tailwindcss/typography` (`prose` classes)
- **Auth**: Supabase Auth, email + password
- **Storage**: NONE — markdown content lives in `markdown_files.content` (TEXT). Do NOT use Supabase Storage.
- **Realtime**: NOT used in v1. Refetch on focus / after mutation.
- **Deployment**: Local `next dev` only for the hackathon.

---

## UI Direction

Original branding, GitHub-inspired layout for markdown screens. Clean,
minimal, dense enough to feel professional. Use shadcn/ui primitives
everywhere; don't hand-roll buttons/inputs.

### Composer (write a new MD or edit an existing one)
GitHub-style **Write / Preview tab toggle** (use shadcn `Tabs`):
- Above the tabs: title input, README input (1-3 lines), tag multi-select
- "Write" tab: a `<textarea>` for the markdown body (monospace font,
  min-height ~400px, full available width)
- "Preview" tab: live rendered preview using the same `MDViewer` component
  (so the viewer and preview look identical)
- Below the tabs: "Save" + "Save & request share to another team" actions
- Show the team this will be saved into; if the user is in only one team,
  default to it; otherwise let them pick

### Viewer (click an MD to read it — `/md/[mdId]`)
GitHub-style file view. Two-column layout:
- **Header bar**: title, tag pills, author avatar + name + Coworker Grade
  badge, last-updated timestamp, "Share" button, "Edit" button (visible to
  author or owning-team lead)
- **Main panel (left, takes most of the width)**: rendered markdown body
  inside a `prose` container. Provide a "Source" toggle that swaps in the
  raw markdown in a monospace block.
- **Sidebar (right, ~320px)**:
  - README (the author's short description)
  - Owning team
  - Teams it's shared with (from `md_team_visibility`)
  - Rating summary (avg stars + count) and a "Rate this" stars input
    (the input is hidden for the author of the MD — they cannot rate their
    own MD)

### Team Feed (`/teams/[teamId]`)
List view of MDs visible to the current user in that team:
- Card per MD: title, tag pills, author with grade, snippet of README,
  rating average, last-updated timestamp
- Top filter bar: tag filter, author filter, sort (recent / top-rated)
- Prominent "Share new MD" CTA → `/teams/[teamId]/compose`

### Dashboard (`/dashboard`)
Landing after login:
- "My teams" list (with quick links into each)
- "Recent across my teams" feed
- "Pending in my inbox" badge → `/inbox`

### Inbox (`/inbox`)
Two sections:
- Direct shares (MDs sent to you 1:1)
- Pending approvals — only visible to team leads:
  - Incoming join requests
  - Incoming cross-team share requests

### User profile (`/u/[userId]`)
- Display name, role, Coworker Grade (large), total ratings, MD count
- List of their MDs you can see

---

## Database Schema Reference

Read `schema.sql` for the canonical schema. Summary:

```
companies           id, name, slug (citext, derived from email domain), created_at
profiles            id (= auth.uid()), company_id, display_name, role, created_at
teams               id, company_id, name, description, lead_id, created_at
team_members        id, team_id, user_id, joined_at
markdown_files      id, team_id, author_id, title, readme, content (TEXT), tags, created_at, updated_at
md_team_visibility  id, md_id, team_id, granted_at      -- cross-team read access
join_requests       id, team_id, user_id, status, message, resolved_at, created_at
cross_team_requests id, md_id, from_team_id, to_team_id, requested_by, status, resolved_at, created_at
direct_shares       id, md_id, sender_id, recipient_id, message, seen, created_at
md_feedback         id, md_id, user_id, stars (1-5), comment, created_at

VIEW md_rating_summary  md_id, avg_stars, rating_count
VIEW user_grades        user_id, display_name, company_id, coworker_grade, total_ratings, md_count
```

### Enums
```
user_role:       'member' | 'lead' | 'admin'
md_tag:          'skill' | 'rule' | 'prompt' | 'sop' | 'other'
approval_status: 'pending' | 'approved' | 'rejected'
```

### Company auto-binding
On signup, the `handle_new_user()` trigger derives the company slug from
the user's email domain. The first user from a new domain auto-creates a
company and is promoted to `admin`; subsequent users from the same domain
auto-join that company as `member`. This is what enforces the "workers
locked to the same company ecosystem" requirement — there is no invite
flow in v1.

### Cross-team sharing model
An MD always belongs to its owning team (`markdown_files.team_id`). To
share into another team, a member creates a `cross_team_requests` row.
When the target team lead approves it, the app inserts a row into
`md_team_visibility` granting that team read access. The original team's
ownership never changes. There is no `is_approved` column — visibility
is purely controlled by `md_team_visibility`.

### Coworker Grade
Each MD can be rated 1-5 stars by anyone who can see it (except the
author). The `user_grades` view aggregates a user's average rating
across all their MDs as `coworker_grade`. Display this prominently on
the user profile and as a small badge next to the author's name on MD
cards / viewer header. If the user has no ratings yet, show "—" rather
than 0.00.

---

## Critical Rules

### Supabase Client Usage
ALWAYS use the correct Supabase client for the context:

```typescript
// SERVER components, route handlers, server actions:
import { createServerClient } from '@supabase/ssr'
import { cookies } from 'next/headers'

// CLIENT components (with 'use client'):
import { createBrowserClient } from '@supabase/ssr'
```

NEVER use the basic `createClient` from `@supabase/supabase-js` in server code.
NEVER expose the service role key in client-side code.
NEVER use `supabase.auth.admin` in client-side code.

### Environment Variables
```
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL        ← safe client-side
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY   ← safe client-side (RLS protects data)
SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY       ← SERVER ONLY, never in client components
```

### TypeScript Types
Always type Supabase responses against `lib/types.ts`. Never use `any`.

### Markdown Security
ALWAYS sanitize with DOMPurify before rendering. No exceptions.

```typescript
// components/MDViewer.tsx
import ReactMarkdown from 'react-markdown'
import DOMPurify from 'dompurify'
import remarkGfm from 'remark-gfm'

export function MDViewer({ content }: { content: string }) {
  const clean = DOMPurify.sanitize(content)
  return (
    <div className="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <ReactMarkdown remarkPlugins={[remarkGfm]}>{clean}</ReactMarkdown>
    </div>
  )
}
```

The same `MDViewer` is used inside the composer's "Preview" tab and on the
viewer page, so they always render identically.

---

## Security Model

**Row Level Security (RLS) handles all access control at the database level.**
You do NOT need permission checks in your API code.

Key rules enforced by RLS (see `rls-policies.sql`):
- Users only see data from their own company
- An MD is visible if it's in your team, shared into one of your teams via
  `md_team_visibility`, or sent directly to you
  (centralized in the `can_view_md()` SQL helper)
- Only team leads can approve join requests and cross-team shares
- Only the target team lead can insert into `md_team_visibility`
- A user cannot rate their own MDs
- Helper functions (`is_team_member`, `can_view_md`, etc.) are
  `SECURITY DEFINER` to avoid recursive-policy bugs

**Never bypass RLS.** Use the service role key only for trusted admin jobs.

---

## Common Supabase Patterns

### Fetch a team's MDs (with author + rating summary)
```typescript
const { data } = await supabase
  .from('markdown_files')
  .select(`
    id, title, readme, tags, created_at, updated_at,
    author:profiles(id, display_name),
    rating:md_rating_summary(avg_stars, rating_count)
  `)
  .eq('team_id', teamId)
  .order('updated_at', { ascending: false })
```

### Create a new MD (member shares to their own team)
```typescript
const { data, error } = await supabase
  .from('markdown_files')
  .insert({
    team_id: teamId,
    author_id: userId,
    title,
    readme,
    content,        // raw markdown body
    tags
  })
  .select('id')
  .single()
```

### Read an MD for the viewer
```typescript
const { data } = await supabase
  .from('markdown_files')
  .select(`
    *,
    author:profiles(id, display_name),
    team:teams(id, name),
    visibility:md_team_visibility(team:teams(id, name)),
    rating:md_rating_summary(avg_stars, rating_count)
  `)
  .eq('id', mdId)
  .single()
```

### Submit a join request
```typescript
await supabase.from('join_requests').insert({
  team_id: teamId,
  user_id: currentUserId,
  message: optionalMessage
})
```

### Approve a join request (team lead only)
```typescript
await supabase
  .from('join_requests')
  .update({ status: 'approved', resolved_at: new Date().toISOString() })
  .eq('id', requestId)

await supabase
  .from('team_members')
  .insert({ team_id: teamId, user_id: applicantUserId })
```

### Approve a cross-team share (target team lead only)
```typescript
// 1. Mark the request approved
await supabase
  .from('cross_team_requests')
  .update({ status: 'approved', resolved_at: new Date().toISOString() })
  .eq('id', requestId)

// 2. Grant read access to the target team
await supabase
  .from('md_team_visibility')
  .insert({ md_id: mdId, team_id: targetTeamId })
```

### Send a direct share
```typescript
await supabase.from('direct_shares').insert({
  md_id: mdId,
  sender_id: currentUserId,
  recipient_id: colleagueId,
  message: optionalNote
})
```

### Rate an MD (1-5 stars, idempotent)
```typescript
await supabase
  .from('md_feedback')
  .upsert(
    { md_id: mdId, user_id: currentUserId, stars, comment },
    { onConflict: 'md_id,user_id' }
  )
```

### Get an author's Coworker Grade
```typescript
const { data } = await supabase
  .from('user_grades')
  .select('coworker_grade, total_ratings, md_count')
  .eq('user_id', authorId)
  .single()
```

### Get current user's profile + company
```typescript
const { data: { user } } = await supabase.auth.getUser()
const { data: profile } = await supabase
  .from('profiles')
  .select('*, company:companies(id, name, slug)')
  .eq('id', user!.id)
  .single()
```

